Jun 26 2006	Not so special	Booked the Sydney House for a our twice yearly one night theatre stay based on previous reviews.The hotel is pleasant enough having been converted from a large Victorian Town House and has a modern, contemporary feel. Our room was on the 3rd floor at the rear and was VERY small with an even smaller bathroom (so small, the door had to be closed to move within it!) The two of us getting ready rfequired a lot of coordination to ensure we could both move around freely! Apart from the size issue, the rooms were well fitted out, quiet (at least at the rear of the property.....the frontage is onto a fairly busy road) and the beds very comfy. Because it is a converted house the floors also creak and the lift has been added as an afer thought....again so small that the two us crammed inside it whilst the porter ran and carried our luggage up the stairs to meet us! The service was, in hindsight, typical of a small, independant, boutique hotel.....very stuffy and not particularly freindly. Upon our arrival the reception clerk (who I later learnt to be the manager) looked down his nose at us and made us feel extremely unwelcome. When it was established that we did in fact have a reservation, he proceeded to treat me as if it was the first time I had ever been in a hotel, explaining in very terse terms that he required my credit card as a deposit for any charges. I am a young but extremely well travelled individual and although we may have booked via a discount agency and been looking &quot;casual&quot; for the trendy streets of Chelsea I did not appreciate being treated like a third class citizen! We did not sample the food/bar due to there seemingly being a small scale conference going on in there although we were not informed of this. Having said that, the room service menu did look quite appertising and reasonably priced.In summary, not a good experience for us and I hope it was just an off day for the staff. If you live with extremely confined spaces then it's fine but personally I will not be visiting again. In keeping with the location the hotel seems to be living off it's contemporary styling rather than its service and practicality and in my opinion there are far more superior rooms and staff within London	
Jun 26 2006	Nice hotel pleasant spot	Just got back from a three night stay in London at the Sydney House Chelsea Hotel. Tend to agree with everything that the reviewer said on 1 April. We had a similar room - the king deluxe on the first floor with the little balconies for £165 per night (booked via the hotel's website). Haven't stayed at other London hotel's so not sure if this is good value or not. The room was not large though well arranged. About 3 feet on one side of the king bed and about 6 feet on the other side. Flat screen tv on the wall, desk area and inbuilt couch. Nicely decorated - very subtle tones of creams and browns. Both my husband and I had laptops, so we appreciated the inroom safe big enough to fit the laptops. Managed to get unsecured wireless from a neighbouring office which was good. The bathroom was lovely but the shower head was so high I could not reach it and the water only came out in torrents. The area is fairly residential - definitely not in the heart of things. But, a gorgeous area to be in with some nice restaurants and shops nearby. We found we spent a lot of time on the tube getting to places we wanted to be. Overall, a very pleasant stay, but we didn't actually spend much time at the hotel other than sleeping.	
Apr 20 2006	Great boutique hotel - downside room noise	Modern boutique hotel. Perfectly presented rooms, good quality if expensive breakfast (£15 each incl. coffee, good, quiet (road noise wise) and convenient location. Friendly and helpful staff.Downside, showers that fluctuate from cold to scalding in a second and noise from rooms above (4th floor) as it seems they have wood floors and every chair movement and bed movement is amplified to rooms on the 3rd floor.	
Apr 1 2006	Subtlety Service Superb Location	I was very pleased to have stayed at Sydney House for two nights, March 28 - 30. My room was #11, a Premier Deluxe with a king bed. I paid 165 pounds per night, taxes included, which I reserved from the hotel's Web site.The room was on the first floor and featured twin Juliet balconies overlooking Sydney Street. It was one of only a very few that have external space. I'm not a smoker, but as this is a non-smoking hotel, these might come in useful for tobacco users!Service is unobtrusive and polite. Check-in and check-out were handled quickly and without complications, and the staff had arranged for me to go to the Aquila gym, with whom they have a partnership. All wake-up calls were executed precisely at the agreed time -- the wake-up call consists of classical music played over the phone. I did not dine at the hotel, nor visit their lobby bar.The room is well-insulated from the outside, but I could hear doors closing in the hall and voices in the room next to me. Given that all rooms have hardwood floors, I was lucky not to have heard footsteps above.There is no iron or ironing board in the room, however they will deliver them to the room upon request.The bath in room #11 is rather tight...one must squeeze around to door to access the commode. The shower is all you get -- no bath in this room, althought other rooms have both. Request ahead if you need to soak. Bath products are by The White Company. The design of the bathroom is, aside from its size, quite strikingly all-glass, and impeccably clean. In fact, the room as a whole was clean and in fresh condition.The location of the hotel is exceptional...walking- distance close to South Kensington tube station, Kings Road and Sloan Square shops and the V&amp;A/Natural History museum complex.I would stay here again without any hesitation.	
Jan 11 2006	Sleek sheik modern boutique	My partner and I stayed in the SYDNEY HOUSE for four nights in January of 2006. We booked the least expensive room, which was small yet comfortable. Accompanying photos are from rooms 40 and 41 on the fourth floor.This little hotel is ideal for those who enjoy modern design botique hotels. Every detail of the modern Euro-style design is methodically planned, and the attention to lighting makes small spaces seem larger. The hotel's online photos and marketing materials give a remarkably accurate picture of the feel of the hotel (see also my &quot;candid&quot; shots).Located adjacent to the sheik neighborhood of Chelsea (nearest &quot;tube&quot; stop is South Kensignton), the hotel is wonderfully situated for those who want to be outside of tourist-hell, yet in a neighborhood with an abundance of good restaurants and shops.Service is professional and friendly.I would like to award the hotel a perfect rating of 5, but the following imperfections make this a 4.5 rating:* Water temperature in shower fluctuates rapidly between cold and hot (be nimble or run the risk of getting scalded).* Housekeeping service fails to replinish soap bottles, even when they are empty.* The two bedside reading lamps are connected to same switch. If you're accustomed to stay up reading while your partner sleeps, you don't have your own light switch (we solved this problem simply by unscrewing one of the bedside light bulbs, but a flaw in design, nonetheless).Despite these imperfections, I would highly recommend this hotel.	
